Assumptions RHEL10 server with the following installed
podman, bootc, and bootc-image-builder installed



podman pull registry.redhat.io/rhel10/rhel-bootc

This image contains the kernel, initrd, and bootloader components needed for IBM Z.


Create a Containerfile to define additional packages and configuration:


FROM registry.redhat.io/rhel10/rhel-bootc
RUN dnf install -y your-packages

podman build -t my-rhel10-bootc .


Use bootc-image-builder to create a disk image (raw or qcow2) for s390x:

bootc-image-builder --target s390x --image my-rhel10-bootc --output /path/to/image.raw

 Deploy the Image

Upload the image to your IBM Z environment.
Use zipl (IBM Z bootloader) to configure boot parameters.
Boot the system from the generated image.

Manage Updates
Instead of dnf update, use:

sudo bootc upgrade

This pulls a new container image and performs an atomic update. Rollback is easy:

sudo bootc rollback

For faster updates, RHEL 10 supports soft reboot using systemctl soft-reboot to avoid full hardware POST cycles


Step by Step

#1 Build the bootc Container Image (RHEL 10, s390x


# Authenticate to Red Hat registry (requires subscription)
podman login registry.redhat.io

# Pull the RHEL 10 bootc base image
podman pull registry.redhat.io/rhel10/rhel-bootc:latest

#2 Create a Containerfile


FROM registry.redhat.io/rhel10/rhel-bootc:latest

# Example baseline packages; tailor to your stack

COPY rpms/ /tmp/rpms/
RUN rpm -Uvh /tmp/rpms/*.rpm

RUN dnf -y install \
    openssh-server \
    vim \
    curl \
    policycoreutils \
    chrony \
    rsyslog \
    # storage & s390x tooling
    s390utils-base \
    zipl \
    dracut \
    # optional: FIPS, compliance, monitoring
    # scap-security-guide \
    # tuned \
    && dnf -y clean all

# Enable services you need at boot
RUN systemctl enable sshd rsyslog chronyd

# Create an admin user (example)
RUN useradd -m -G wheel britley && echo 'britley:changeme' | chpasswd

# Harden SSH defaults at build-time (immutable at runtime)
RUN sed -i 's/^#PasswordAuthentication yes/PasswordAuthentication no/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config

# Optional: Inject SSH pubkey (for initial remote access)
# COPY britley.pub /root/.ssh/authorized_keys

#3 Build the image

podman build -t quay.io/yourns/rhel10-bootc-s390x:base .

#4 Test-run as a container

podman run --rm -it quay.io/yourns/rhel10-bootc-s390x:base /bin/bash

#5 Convert the bootc Image to a Bootable Disk (s390x

Install bootc-image-builder (on build host)
On RHEL 10/9.5:

sudo dnf -y install bootc-image-builder

#6 Build a raw image for s390x


bootc-image-builder \
  --image quay.io/yourns/rhel10-bootc-s390x:base \
  --target s390x \
  --output /var/tmp/rhel10-bootc-s390x.raw

#7 Deploy on IBM Z LPAR


# Example: copy to KVM host

scp /var/tmp/rhel10-bootc-s390x.raw root@kvm-host:/var/lib/images/

If your image boots but lacks NIC/DASD drivers, add dracut modules in the Containerfile and rebuild

#8 LPAR (DASD/FCP) boot notes

If you deploy to LPAR and need to prepare boot on a disk:

Ensure zipl is installed (included above).
Ensure device drivers (rd.zfcp, rd.dasd, rd.net) are present in initrd via dracut config.
Configure /etc/zipl.conf, then run:

zipl -v

#9 First Boot

# On the VM/LPAR
ssh britley@<ip-of-system>
uname -a
cat /etc/os-release
systemctl status sshd


#10 Atomic updates (Image Mode)


# Pull and stage new OS image, then reboot into it
sudo bootc upgrade
# If image switch is needed (e.g., staging→prod tag):
sudo bootc switch quay.io/yourns/rhel10-bootc-s390x:prod


sudo bootc rollback

sudo systemctl soft-reboot


 docker run --privileged --security-opt seccomp=unconfined -it --name rhel10-lab01 registry.redhat.io/rhel10/rhel-bootc /bin/bash

sudo dnf install -y fuse-overlayfs
 Modify /etc/rhsm/rhsm.conf
proxy = http://10.2.16.17:8080 
dnf --setopt=sslverify=false install fuse-overlayfs

docker pull registry.redhat.io/rhel10/bootc-image-builder:latest

subscription-manager register --insecure


podman login --tls-verify=false registry.redhat.io


podman build \
  --platform linux/s390x \
  --tls-verify=false \
  -t images.pkgrepo.bcbssc.com/mu94/rhel10-bootc-s390x:base \
  -f containerfile \
  .


sudo mkdir -p /etc/containers/containers.conf.d
printf "[network]\nfirewall_driver=\"none\"\n" | \
  sudo tee /etc/containers/containers.conf.d/90-firewall-none.conf


podman build \
  --network=host \
  --platform linux/s390x \
  --tls-verify=false \
  -t images.pkgrepo.bcbssc.com/mu94/rhel10-bootc-s390x:base \
  -f containerfile \
  --volume /etc/pki/entitlement:/etc/pki/entitlement:ro \
  --volume /etc/rhsm:/etc/rhsm:ro \
  --volume /etc/yum.repos.d/redhat.repo:/etc/yum.repos.d/redhat.repo:ro \
  .

FROM registry.redhat.io/rhel10/rhel-bootc

# Install baseline packages (includes s390x tools)
RUN dnf -y install \
      openssh-server \
      vim \
      curl \
      policycoreutils \
      chrony \
      rsyslog \
      s390utils-base \
      zipl \
      dracut \
  && dnf -y clean all

# Enable services
RUN systemctl enable sshd rsyslog chronyd

# Create admin user
RUN useradd -m -G wheel ts00zu && echo 'ts00zu:changeme' | chpasswd

# Harden SSH
RUN sed -i 's/^#\?PasswordAuthentication .*/PasswordAuthentication no/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config


subscription-manager repos \
  --enable=rhel-10-for-s390x-baseos-rpms \
  --enable=rhel-10-for-s390x-appstream-rpms




curl -k -o /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/redhat-uep.pem https://cdn.redhat.com/redhat-uep.pem

update-ca-trust extract


.\Build-RHEL10-BootcDisk.ps1 -BootcImage images.pkgrepo.bcbssc.com/mu94/rhel10-bootc-s390x:base `
                               -OutputPath "C:\Users\YourUser\output" `
                               -ImageType qcow2

docker login images.pkgrepo.bcbssc.com

docker tag rhel10-new-s390x:stable images.pkgrepo.bcbssc.com/mu94/rhel10-new-s390x:stable
docker push images.pkgrepo.bcbssc.com/mu94/rhel10-new-s390x:stable


docker run --rm -it --privileged --security-opt seccomp=unconfined `
  -v C:\Users\mu94\scripts\s390x-build\output:/output `
  registry.redhat.io/rhel10/bootc-image-builder:latest `
  --type qcow2 --target-arch s390x rhel10-new-s390x




sudo sh -c 'echo "sslverify=false" >> /etc/dnf/dnf.conf'

curl -k -o /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/redhat-uep.pem https://cdn.redhat.com/redhat-uep.pem
sudo update-ca-trust


sudo subscription-manager refresh


sed -i 's/^sslverify = 1/sslverify = 0/g /etc/yum.repos.d/redhat.repo

dnf --setopt=sslverify=false install fuse-overlayfs




deploying a rhel10 raw image to dasd

Auto


Upgrade Copilot


January 28
You said:
deploying a rhel10 raw image to dasd
Copilot said:
Copilot
Below is a clean, accurate, s390x‑specific workflow for deploying a RHEL 10 raw disk image onto IBM Z DASD, using only what Red Hat actually documents today.

The key points from the Red Hat Enterprise Linux 10 documentation are:

RHEL 10 supports outputting disk images in raw format via bootc‑image‑builder
redhat
RHEL 10 bootc images officially support IBM Z (s390x) as a target architecture
redhat
Raw disk images are an officially supported bootc output type (“raw – Unformatted raw disk”)
redhat
✅ Overview: Deploying a RHEL 10 Raw Disk Image to DASD (IBM Z / s390x)
Deployment consists of three phases:

Build the RHEL 10 raw disk image
Prepare the DASD device (activate, format, partition)
Write the raw image to the DASD device and make it IPL‑bootable
1. Build the RHEL 10 Raw Disk Image (bootc‑image‑builder)
RHEL 10 uses image mode, producing disk images from a container image using bootc‑image‑builder.

Supported output types include raw disk images.
redhat

Example: Build a raw RHEL 10 disk image



Shell
podman run --rm -it \
  -v $(pwd):/output \
  registry.redhat.io/rhel10/bootc-image-builder:latest \
  build \
  --type raw \
  --image registry.redhat.io/rhel10/rhel-bootc:latest \
  /output
This produces something like:

rhel10-bootc.raw
2. Prepare the DASD device on IBM Z
2.1 Activate DASD
On Linux (LPAR or z/VM):




Shell
echo 1 > /sys/bus/ccw/devices/0.0.XXXX/online
2.2 Low‑level format DASD (if blank)



Shell
dasdfmt -b 4096 -y /dev/dasdX
(4096‑byte blocks recommended for modern Linux DASD.)

2.3 Create a partition table



Shell
fdasd -a /dev/dasdX
This creates a single Linux partition /dev/dasdX1.

3. Deploy the Raw Disk Image to DASD
Since the bootc‑image‑builder raw output is a complete disk image, you can write it directly to the DASD device.

⚠️ Ensure the target DASD is not mounted.

3.1 Write the raw image



Shell
dd if=rhel10-bootc.raw of=/dev/dasdX bs=64M status=progress
sync
This writes the full disk image—including bootloader, kernel, and partitions—onto the DASD.

4. Install zIPL Bootloader (if needed)
Most image‑mode raw images include the bootloader, but if you customized the image, re‑installing zIPL ensures IPL bootability:




Shell
mount /dev/dasdX1 /mnt
zipl --verbose --target /mnt
umount /mnt
5. IPL the DASD
From HMC or z/VM:

IPL <device number>
System should come up into RHEL 10 using the bootc image’s defined configuration.

✔ Summary
Step	Purpose
Build raw image	Use bootc‑image‑builder to output a raw disk image (supported).
Prepare DASD	Activate, low‑level format, partition.
Deploy	dd the raw image directly to the DASD device.
Bootloader	Optional zIPL reinstall (image usually contains one).
IPL	Boot the system normally on IBM Z.
If you want, I can also generate:

✅ A full automation script (Ansible or Bash)
✅ A Kickstart + bootc workflow for s390x
✅ A workflow specific to z/VM, KVM on IBM Z, or LPAR

Just tell me your target environment inside IBM Z.

