You said:
how to pass my containerfile to podman during build
Copilot said:
Copilot
You can pass your Containerfile to podman build in three different ways, depending on where the file is located and what you want to name it.

Here’s the quick guide:

✅ 1. Use a local Containerfile with -f (most common)
If your file is named something other than Containerfile or Dockerfile:




Shell
podman build -f ./MyContainerfile -t myimage:latest .
Explanation:

-f specifies the path to your Containerfile
The final . is the build context (directory whose contents are available to ADD/COPY)
✅ 2. Use a Containerfile named Containerfile or Dockerfile (automatic discovery)
If your file is literally named:

Containerfile
Dockerfile
…then you don’t need to specify -f:




Shell
podman build -t myimage:latest .
Podman automatically looks for:

Containerfile
Dockerfile
…in that order.

✅ 3. Pass a remote Containerfile (URL)
Podman can build directly from a remote Containerfile:




Shell
podman build -f https://example.com/mycontainerfile -t myimage:latest .
✅ 4. Pass stdin as your Containerfile
Useful for CI pipelines or dynamically generated files:




Shell
cat MyContainerfile | podman build -t myimage:latest -f -
-f - tells Podman to read the Containerfile from stdin.

Example with your RHEL 10 bootc workloads
If you have a custom Containerfile sitting in the current directory:




Shell
podman build -f Containerfile.rhel10 -t quay.io/myuser/rhel10-bootc:latest .
Need help writing an optimal Containerfile for your RHEL10 bootc image?
I can help you build:

a minimal bootc Containerfile
one that includes cloud-init
one that embeds your DASD configs
or one tailored for z/VM, LPAR, or KVM on IBM Z
Just tell me what you want included.








You said:
how to find the kernel type in linux
Copilot said:
Copilot
Here are the most reliable ways to find the kernel type in Linux, depending on what exactly you mean by “kernel type” (version, architecture, build type, etc.). No search needed — these are universal Linux commands.

✅ 1. Find the kernel version (full string)



Shell
uname -r
Example output:

5.14.0-503.11.1.el9_4.s390x
This tells you:

Kernel version
Patch level
Distribution tag
Architecture (e.g., s390x, x86_64, ppc64le, aarch64)
✅ 2. Find the kernel architecture



Shell
uname -m
Typical outputs:

x86_64
aarch64
s390x
ppc64le
This is extremely useful on IBM Z to confirm you're running s390x.

✅ 3. Find the kernel type and OS info



Shell
uname -a
Example:

Linux myhost 5.14.0-503.11.1.el9_4.s390x #1 SMP Tue Jan 14 12:22:54 UTC 2025 s390x s390x s390x GNU/Linux
This gives:

Kernel name
Hostname
Kernel version
Build date
CPU architecture
OS type
✅ 4. Find kernel build configuration (“features”)
Most Linux distros ship kernel configs in /boot/.

To inspect full kernel capabilities:




Shell
zcat /proc/config.gz | less
If not available:




Shell
less /boot/config-$(uname -r)
This tells you things like:

Whether CONFIG_KVM is enabled
Filesystem support
Security modules
CPU tuning flags
✅ 5. Find whether the kernel is SMP, PREEMPT, RT, etc.
Run:




Shell
uname -v
Or inspect the full version string:




Shell
uname -a
Look for flags like:

SMP (Symmetric Multi‑Processing)
PREEMPT (low latency)
RT (real‑time)
Let me know what you specifically need:
Kernel architecture (x86_64, s390x, etc.)
Whether kernel is RT, PREEMPT, SMP
Whether your kernel has specific modules
RHEL bootc image kernel type
Happy to tailor the commands for IBM Z, RHEL 10, or image‑mode bootc systems.








You said:
how to add a container tarball to podman
Copilot said:
Copilot
Here are the correct ways to add (load or import) a container tarball into Podman, depending on the tarball format and your goal.

✅ 1. Load a Docker/OCI tarball into Podman
If your tarball was created with:

podman save
docker save
OR is an OCI image layout in a tarball
Use:




Shell
podman load -i myimage.tar
After loading, list images:




Shell
podman images
This is the most common workflow when someone gives you a .tar image export.

✅ 2. Load and tag the image
If the tarball doesn't include a tag or you want to assign a new one:




Shell
podman load -i myimage.tar --alias myrepo/myimage:latest
✅ 3. Load an OCI directory instead of a tarball
If you have already extracted it:




Shell
podman load --input oci-dir/
✅ 4. Import a root filesystem tarball (NOT a saved image)
If your tarball is a filesystem snapshot, not a saved container image, use:




Shell
podman import rootfs.tar mycustomimage:latest
Use import only for rootfs archives.
It creates an image but without history/layers.

When to use which?
What you have	Correct command
.tar file created by podman save	podman load -i file.tar
.tar file created by docker save	podman load -i file.tar
OCI layout tarball	podman load -i file.tar
Extracted OCI directory	podman load --input oci-dir/
Tarball of a container’s filesystem only	podman import file.tar
If you want, I can show you:
how to save → transfer → load images cleanly
how to load bootc container images
how to use a tarball with bootc-image-builder
how to push the tarball into a local registry
Just tell me your workflow.








You said:
how to remove an image from podman
Copilot said:
Copilot
Removing an image from Podman is simple. Here are the supported ways:

✅ 1. Remove an image by name or tag



Shell
podman rmi myimage:latest
If the image is not used by any containers, it will be removed immediately.

✅ 2. Remove an image by image ID
List images:




Shell
podman images
Then remove by ID:




Shell
podman rmi <image-id>
✅ 3. Force remove (even if containers exist)
If a container is using the image, Podman will refuse to remove it unless you force:




Shell
podman rmi -f myimage:latest
✅ 4. Remove all unused images
Cleanup dangling/unreferenced images:




Shell
podman image prune -f
Or prune everything not in use:




Shell
podman image prune --all -f
Quick Notes
If the image is in use by a running container, stop it first:



Shell
podman stop <container>
podman rm <container>
podman rmi <image>
Removing a tag of a multi‑tagged image just removes the tag, not the underlying layers.
If you want, I can help you:

Remove all images except specific ones
Clean up all containers + images safely
Inspect what’s blocking an image from being removed
Just tell me your case!





